git cheatsheet

1. git checkout {commit id} - This is will allow you to view the previous commit of git with the git id, and will erase all changes made after that time... This will cause branching.
2. git add . - This adds the root directory of the file to git to be watched.
3. git add {file-name} - This adds the file to git to be watched.
4. git commit -m {message} - This commits changes to git with the particular message explaining the commit.
5. git commit -m {message} --amend - Updates previous commit instead of creating a new commit.
5. git log - Shows all the commits made previously and the commit id, with the user who committed the changes.
6. git init - To initialize a git reposito ry.
7. ls - To list all the files under the current directory.
8. git status - To check if there's any change to be committed into git.
9. git log --all - Shows all the commmit history with the ones made ahead that were previously cleared by using `git checkout {commit id}`
10. git log --all --graph - Shows all the commmit history in form of branches.
11. git checkout {commit id} {file-name / .} - This does the same thing as number 1, but it doesn't cause branching, and it actually restores to previous version instead of just viewing it and re-committing again.
12. git status - This checks if there's any file that needs to be committed.


Setting Shortcuts on git.

12. git config --global alias.s "status" - This sets a shortcut of `git s` instead of writing git status.
13. git confit --global alias.cm "commit -m" - This sets a shortcut of `git commit -m`.

I can still update others to save some time.


Ignoring files from being saved on version history
 - Create a file named .gitignore and put the info inside, it won't be added when saving to git.


Removing a project from git tracking

 - On powershell: Remove-Item -Recurse -Force .git
 - On CMD: rm -rf .git